                "Currently, all files in the Veloren repo are licensed under GPLv3, including assets. This may cause problems for several reasons.\n1. GPL requires the source code files to be made available. What this means for assets is entirely unclear. In the context of music, does this mean that the project files need to be made available? Usually, this also requires plugins and programs that not everyone has or can obtain. These project files can also be quite large. The MIDI? MIDI only tells half the story, and is also not truly the original file. In the context of sound effects, similar arguments can be made. In the context of visual assets like `.png`s and `.vox`s, it could be argued that they serve as their own source files.\n2. What happens when an outsider wants to use the music for e.g. a video? GPL may suggest that since the music is licensed under GPL, the video needs to be as well. This is a ridiculous notion. Simply disallowing creators from using our music feels like going against our values.\n3. Currently, creators of assets usually do not explicitly agree to licensing their assets under GPL - rather, it's the creator of the MR that does this.\n\nI offer a solution in the form of a total license switch for assets - if not for all assets, then at least sound and music.\n\nThe license should deal primarily with finished assets rather than source code. It should allow for relatively free copying but also require accreditation. Creators should also be made to agree explicitly to license their assets under this license, preferably upon submission.\n\nA potential plan of action is as follows:\n- Announce a license change on the Discord, and call for creators to give permission to switch.\n- Add the new license to the `LICENSE` file and specify which filetypes fall under it.\n- Create a new channel(s) in the Discord specifically for asset submission; make it very clear that all files uploaded to the channel are to be licensed under the new license upon being added to the repo.\n- If creators do not answer or otherwise do not give permission to swap licenses, temporarily take their assets out of the game until they do.\n\nPotential licenses to switch to:\n- Creative Commons BY 4.0 (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/): free sharing and adaptation is allowed so long as attribution is provided.\n- Creative Commons BY-NC 4.0 (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/): same as BY except commercial uses are not allowed.\n- Creative Commons BY-SA 4.0 (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/): same as BY except all transformations of the material must use the same license. Out of all the CC licenses, this is the most similar to the original GPLv3.\n- Creative Commons BY-NC-SA 4.0 (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/): same as BY except commercial uses are not allowed *and* any adaptations must use the same license.\n\nUnsurprisingly, the best/most obvious alternatives are all Creative Commons. Which specific license is up for debate, and really depends on the goals of the project.",
